<HEADLINE>
<P>
PACIFIC WATCH: CHINA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Automotive Blueprint Published: The government unveiled its plan for 
developing an automotive industry that can satisfy demand for car ownership by 
the country's 300 million families, targeting a 90% market share for 
Chinese-based plants by the end of the century. The long-awaited Automotive 
Industry Policy, approved by Premier Li Peng in March and published in the 
People's Daily last week, calls for removal of obstacles to private car 
ownership and introduces measures severely limiting foreign access to the huge 
market. The policy restricts car imports to six ports of entry and rules that 
the number and type of foreign cars bought must be approved by the State 
Council, China's Cabinet. 
</P>
