<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94 / QUARTERFINALS; SPOTLIGHT; ECONOMY CLASS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PAUL HAYWARD, Daily Telegraph of London 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In reflecting on the precarious finances of the Bulgarian team: 
</P>
<P>
 "This is a country that has qualified for six of the nine World Cup finals 
since 1962, though it had never won a match before this year's competition and 
was on the fringes of bankruptcy before securing passage to America. 
</P>
<P>
 "The sadder stories become less painful with each odds-bucking victory.Few 
Bulgarians will care to reflect that when he asked if he could travel last year 
to examine his foreign-based players, Coach Dimitar Penev was told he would 
have to buy a rucksack and stick out his thumb if he was to get past the 
Bulgarian border. Now his team is in the heart of preppy America walking down a 
cultural catwalk with the world championship looking into view. 
</P>
<P>
 " 'This is a beautiful stadium,' Penev said when he first saw the great 
shimmering arena shared by the New York Giants and Jets. 'I wish we could take 
it home with us.' " 
</P>
</TEXT>
